{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fbeb06f4-1ea3-41e7-b3d2-4d1e2745bf81","content":"## What's Happening\n\n**.NET raised the x86-64 baseline microarchitecture level.** Starting with .NET 10, the minimum was bumped from **x86-64-v1** to **x86-64-v2**, requiring instructions like SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. .NET 11 may raise this further to **x86-64-v3**, which adds **AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA** — instructions unavailable on pre-Haswell (pre-2013) Intel CPUs.\n\nYour 2012-era node likely has a **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge** CPU. These support v2 but **not v3**, which explains why .NET 10 worked but .NET 11 fails.\n\n## How to Confirm\n\nOn the failing node, run:\n\n```bash\n# Check CPU flags\ngrep -oP '(sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|avx|avx2|bmi1|bmi2|fma)' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n\n# Check microarchitecture level support\n/lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 --help 2>&1 | grep supported\n```\n\nIf you see `avx` but **not** `avx2`/`fma`/`bmi2`, the CPU meets v2 but not v3.\n\n## Your Other Platforms Are Fine\n\n| Target | Architecture | Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| Linux x86-64 (2012 HW) | x86-64 (Sandy/Ivy Bridge) | **❌ Fails** — missing v3 instructions |\n| Windows Arm64 (SQ1) | ARMv8.2-A | ✅ Unaffected — Arm64 baseline unchanged |\n| Raspberry Pi 4 | ARMv8-A (Cortex-A72) | ✅ Unaffected — Arm64 baseline unchanged |\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire the 2012 hardware** — replace with Haswell-era (2013+) or newer CPUs.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for workloads targeting that node until hardware is refreshed.\n3. **Check for a compatibility knob** — previous baseline raises included a `DOTNET_EnableSSE3=0`-style opt-out or a v1-baseline runtime package, but these are not guaranteed for every release.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4131f3ab-d8ca-4a0b-b81a-6895f1797f77","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction set requirements. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements — specifically the change in x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2 starting in .NET 10.\n\nLet me explain what's happening.\n\nIn .NET 8+, Microsoft started raising the x86-64 baseline. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: x86-64 baseline (v1) — essentially the original AMD64/Intel 64 instruction set.\n- .NET 9: Still x86-64-v1 baseline.\n\n\n- .NET 10: Microsoft raised the minimum to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT — a known breaking change.\n\nBut wait, the user says they were on .NET 10 and it worked fine, then upgraded to .NET 11 and hit this error. So I need to figure out whether .NET 11 raised the baseline even further, or if something else is going on with their specific setup. this suggests .NET 10 targets x86-64-v2 (compatible with 2012 hardware), but if .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v3, that would require AVX2 which didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013—so older Sandy Bridge/Ivy Bridge systems would fail. The specific shift would be from x86-64-v2 to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA, and other instruction sets that pre-Haswell processors lack. Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge systems would support v2 but not v3. Let me verify the actual .NET timeline — I know .NET 8 and 9 both used v1 as the baseline, though there's been discussion about moving to v2 in future releases. The error message matches exactly what .NET produces when CPU baseline requirements aren't met, so the user's scenario is definitely plausible. Since .NET 10 worked on 2012 hardware but .NET 11 failed, the baseline must have been raised at that boundary—either from v1 to v2, or from v2 to v3. Given that 2012 Sandy Bridge supports v2 but not v3, the most likely scenario is that .NET 11 jumped to requiring x86-64-v3. I'm overcomplicating this. The real issue is that Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline requirement—likely from v1 to v2—in one of these .NET versions, and the 2012 hardware (or at least one node in their cluster) doesn't fully support v2 instructions. That's the breaking change between versions. The other platforms like Windows Arm64 and Raspberry Pi 4 shouldn't have this issue since Arm64 baselines haven't shifted the same way. I should focus on explaining that .NET 11 raised the x86-64 baseline requirement and what they can actually do to fix it on their older hardware.","outputTokens":2942,"requestId":"6817:38B891:27FC396:2BE7EC0:69FD2981"},"id":"b56eae6a-adba-4bd6-849f-cb7887a3a84c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:09:31.052Z","parentId":"37842dcd-3437-479d-a0c0-7bc5b26d5556"}
